To open a Navy Federal Credit Union (NFCU) account in person using your deceased father's military service as eligibility, here's how you can approach it strategically and respectfullyas his son and next of kin:

Step-by-Step: Opening a Navy Federal Account As a Deceased Veteran's Son

1. Confirm Your Eligibility

Navy Federal membership is open to:

  • Active duty, veterans, or retired military (any branch)
  • Immediate family members of current or eligible members, including:
    • Children (biological, adoptive, or stepchildren)
    • Spouses, siblings, grandchildren, etc.

As the biological son of a deceased Army veteran (Vietnam helicopter pilot), you are absolutely eligible for membership.

2. Documents to Bring

When you visit a branch, bring these documents to establish your eligibility:

Your Documents:

  • State ID or Driver's License
  • Social Security Number (SSN)
  • Proof of address (utility bill, lease, or government correspondence if address is not on your ID)

Your Fathers Military Service Documents:

Since he's deceased, these help establish his service:

  • DD-214 (Discharge papers) If available
  • Military ID (even expired or copies)
  • VA or military medical records (optional)
  • Death certificate (optional but helpful)
  • Obituary or funeral program mentioning military service (optional)

You mentioned you have his military ID, drivers license, and even Vietnamese and military currencythese can absolutely help show proof of service.

3. Find a Local Branch

Use this tool to find your nearest NFCU branch: Navy Federal Branch Locator

Youre currently in Florida, near Land O Lakes, so possible branches near you include:

  • Tampa MacDill AFB
  • Tampa West Waters Ave
  • Lakeland
  • Brandon

4. What to Say In Person

Heres how you can present your case respectfully:

Hi, Id like to open a Navy Federal account. My father was a Vietnam veteran who served in the U.S. Army and is now deceased. Im his only son and I have his military ID and related documents. Id like to open a membership based on his service.

5. If You Need to Request His DD-214

If they request a DD-214 and you dont have one, you can request it online:

  • https://www.archives.gov/veterans

But usually a physical visit with strong supporting documents (especially if you're bringing his actual military ID and license) is enough to proceed without it.

Tip: Start with a Share Savings Account

  • Minimum deposit: $5
  • This opens your membership.
  • You can then add a checking account, ATM card, and apply for loans or credit later.

Want Me to Help You Pick a Day?

Let me know what your schedule looks like this week and Ill help:

  • Find the best branch
  • Check its hours
  • Even draft a short script or checklist you can bring

Would you like to go early in the week (Monday/Tuesday), mid-week, or closer to the weekend?

I can also call ahead for you (or write a script you can say or show) to ensure a smooth visit. Lets make this honoring of your fathers legacy a moment of real strength and new foundations.
